{{Infobox officeholder | name = J. Donald Monan, S.J. | order = | image = | caption = | predecessor = W. Seavey Joyce, S.J. | title = 24th President of [[Boston College]] | birth_date = {{Birth date|1924|12|31}} | birth_place = [[Blasdell, New York]] | death_date ={{Death date and age|2017|3|18|1924|12|31}}<ref>{{cite news|title=In Memoriam: Rev. J. Donald Monan, SJ|work=[[Boston College|BC]] News|url=https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/bcnews/campus-community/announcements/in_memoriam_j_donald_monan_sj_24th_president_of_Boston_College.html|date=March 18, 2017|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref> | alma_mater = [[Woodstock College]], [[Université catholique de Louvain]] | religion = [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] | term_start = July 31, 1972 | term_end = July 30, 1996 }} '''J. Donald Monan''', [[Society of Jesus|SJ]] (December 31, 1924 – March 18, 2017) was the Chancellor of [[Boston College]] from 1996 to 2017 and its 24th President from 1972 to 1996—the longest such tenure in the University's history. A native of [[Blasdell, New York]], he joined the [[Society of Jesus]] in 1942. Monan earned a bachelor's degree, a licentiate of philosophy, and a [[Licentiate of Sacred Theology]] at [[Woodstock College]]. He then studied at the [[Université catholique de Louvain]] in Belgium, where he earned a [[Ph.D.]] in philosophy. He was ordained a priest in 1955.<ref>{{cite book|title=History of Boston College: From the Beginnings to 1990|date=1990|publisher=University Press of Boston College|location=Boston|isbn=0962593400|edition=1st}}</ref>
Prior to becoming President of Boston College, Monan served as Acting President, Vice President, Academic Dean, Chairman of the Philosophy Department, Professor and Instructor at [[Le Moyne College]].
==Boston College ==
When Monan took over as President, BC was approximately $30 million in debt and its endowment totaled just under $6 million. By the time he retired, the University's endowment had risen to over $500 million and the campus had greatly expanded to include such new buildings as O’Neill Library, Merkert Chemistry Center and Conte Forum.
Monan has served as Chancellor of the University since retiring as President. Monan's memberships include the [[National Leadership Roundtable on Church Management]], the Jesuit Philosophical Association,<ref>[http://www.sjnen.org/jesuit-jubilee-2012-biographies "2012 Jesuit Jubilarians"]</ref> New England Province of Jesuits. the [[Society for Phenomenology and Existential Philosophy]], and the [[Massachusetts Historical Society]].
