'''Maria Helena Rosas Fernandes''' (born 1933) is a [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]] [[composer]], [[pianist]], [[musicologist]], conductor and music educator.
Fernandes was born in [[Brazópolis]] in [[Minas Gerais]] state, and graduated in piano from the Brazilian Conservatory of Music of [[Guanabara (state)|Guanabara]] State in piano and from the Superior School of Music Santa Marcelina in composition and conducting.
After completing her studies, Fernandes worked as a choral conductor and music teacher at conservatories and published research on [[Music of Brazil|indigenous Brazilian music]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=IvoQQU1QL_QC&pg=PA395&lpg=PA395&dq=Maria+Helena+Rosas+Fernandes+composer#v=onepage&q=Maria%20Helena%20Rosas%20Fernandes%20composer&f=false|title=The Norton/Grove dictionary of women composers|format=Digitized online by GoogleBooks|first=Julie Anne|last=Sadie|first2=Rhian|last2=Samuel|year=1994|accessdate=4 October 2010|isbn=9780393034875}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A Guide to Piano Music by Women Composers: Women born after 1900|author=Dees, Pamela Youngdahl|year=2004}}</ref> Her works have been performed internationally and won awards including the 2006 [[Nancy Van de Vate]] International Composition Prize for Opera for ''Marília de Dirceu''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xs4all.nl/~gdv/vmm/operaprize-int.html|title=2006 Nancy Van de Vate International Composition Prize for Opera|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref>
==Works== Selected works include: *''Prelúdio'' *''Valsa'' *''Cantilena'' *''Canto de Maricatu'' *''''Marília de Dirceu'', opera
Her compositions have been recorded and issued on CD, including: *''Brasileira: Piano Music by Brazilian Women'' (2003) Centaur Records
