{{Infobox video game series |italic title= |genre=Minigame |developer=KnowWare, Smart Games |year of inception=1996 |first release version=Smart Games Challenge |first release date=1996 |latest release version=Smart Games Challenge&nbsp;3 |latest release date=1998 }}
'''''Smart Games Challenge''''' is a video game series developed by KnowWare and Smart Games. Three games were released between 1996-8.
== Gameplay == Each game consists of a series of minigames, designed to improve cognitive function.
==Reception== ===Smart Games Challenge=== ''Smart Games Challenge'' was a commercial success, with 300,000 copies sold by early 1998.<ref name=pcgamerus>{{cite journal | author=Renninger, Lisa H. | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | url=http://www.pcgamer.com:80/reviews/964.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000301120519/http://www.pcgamer.com/reviews/964.html | archivedate=March 1, 2000 | title=''Smart Games Challenge 2'' | date=February 1998 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref>
''Smart Games Challenge'' was a finalist for the [[Game Developers Conference|Computer Game Developers Conference]]'s 1996 "Best Trivia or Puzzle Game" [[Spotlight Awards|Spotlight Award]],<ref name=spotlightnoms1996>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970605172050/http://www.next-generation.com/news/041597e.chtml | url=http://www.next-generation.com:80/news/041597e.chtml | title=And the Nominees Are... | date=April 15, 1997 | author=Staff | work=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] | archivedate=June 5, 1997 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref> but lost the prize to ''[[You Don't Know Jack XL]]''.<ref name=spotlight1997>{{cite press release | url=http://www.gamechoiceawards.com/archive/spotlight_1997.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703083042/http://www.gamechoiceawards.com/archive/spotlight_1997.html | archivedate=July 3, 2011 | title=Spotlight Awards Winners Announced for Best Computer Games of 1996 | publisher=[[Game Developers Conference]] | deadurl=no | location=[[Santa Clara, California]] | date=April 28, 1997 }}</ref> It was also the runner-up for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]''{{'}}s 1996 "Classic/Puzzle Game of the Year" award, which ultimately went to ''[[Baku Baku Animal]]''. The editors called ''Smart Games Challenge'' "an inspired collection of every brain teaser imaginable", and a game that "promises puzzle fans an excellent mental work-out."<ref name=cgwpremier1996>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[Computer Gaming World]] | title=The ''Computer Gaming World'' 1997 Premier Awards |date=May 1997 | issue=154 | pages=68–70, 72, 74, 76, 78, 80 }}</ref> However, it won the [[Software and Information Industry Association#CODiE Awards|Codie award]] for "Best Debut of the Year".<ref name=codie1996winners>{{cite press release | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980210135044/http://www.spa.org/codies/1997/codiewin.htm | url=http://www.spa.org:80/codies/1997/codiewin.htm | title=SPA Hands Out Coveted Codie Awards To Best Software Products of the Year | date=March 3, 1997 | location=[[San Diego]] | archivedate=February 10, 1998 | publisher=Software Publishers Association | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref>
PC Game World gave it 68%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pcgameworld.com/reviews/s/smartgameschallenge1/index.htm|title=Smart Games Challenge 1 game review - PC Gameworld !!!|date=2001-04-17|access-date=2017-12-30|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010417103112/http://www.pcgameworld.com/reviews/s/smartgameschallenge1/index.htm|archivedate=2001-04-17|df=}}</ref> World Village gave it 3/5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.worldvillage.com/wv/gamezone/html/reviews/sg.htm|title=Smart Games Challenge #1|date=2009-05-04|access-date=2017-12-30|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504133510/http://www2.worldvillage.com/wv/gamezone/html/reviews/sg.htm|archivedate=2009-05-04|df=}}</ref>
